    <h2>SECTION A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain prototyping model with a neat diagram. List out its advantages and dis-advantages.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A prototype, which is an early estimate of the final system or product, is constructed, tested, and improved repeatedly until it satisfies user requirements. This process is known as the prototyping model in software development. This methodology is especially helpful in situations when the precise needs are not fully recognized at the outset. Better understanding and visualization of the product by developers and users through prototyping aids in requirement clarification and enhances system usability.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-43833 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/prototyping.drawio.png?resize=241%2C238&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="241" height="238"></p>
<h3>Steps in the Prototyping Model:</h3>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Requirements Gathering and Analysis</strong>: Obtain the users&#8217; fundamental requirements. Usually, these criteria are either vague or unfinished and just reflect the user&#8217;s wants..</li>
<li><strong>Quick Design</strong>: Develop a basic system design. This design just incorporates the essential elements that must be comprehended.</li>
<li><strong>Build Prototype</strong>: During the rapid design phase, create a simple version of the system that just has the essential functionality.</li>
<li><strong>User Evaluation</strong>: Show the prototype to users and get their opinions. Users engage with the prototype, offering recommendations or pointing out aspects that are lacking.</li>
<li><strong>Refinement</strong>: The prototype is adjusted and improved in response to user input. Until the prototype satisfies user expectations, the cycle (Build Prototype → User Evaluation → Refinement) is repeated.</li>
<li><strong>Full Development</strong>: After the prototype is completed and approved, the real system is created with an emphasis on performance, scalability, and dependability.</li>
<li><strong>Testing and Maintenance</strong>: The full-scale system undergoes extensive testing and ongoing maintenance when it is established.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Advantages of the Prototyping Model:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Improved Requirements Understanding</strong> : Enables users to view a functional system model, which aids in the clarification and improvement of requirements.</li>
<li><strong>Better User Involvement</strong> : Users may provide input at an early stage, which improves the quality and usefulness of the finished product.</li>
<li><strong>Flexible Design</strong> : This lowers the chance of failure by allowing for easy modifications as the prototype is constructed and improved.</li>
<li><strong>Lower Risk</strong> : There is a lower chance of creating a system that doesn&#8217;t satisfy user demands when problems are discovered early.</li>
<li><strong>Early Missing Functionality Detection</strong> : Users are able to spot missing features early on in the development process.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Disadvantages of the Prototyping Model:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Scope creep</strong> : As a result of constant adjustments and improvements, the project&#8217;s scope may grow, lengthening its time and raising its cost.</li>
<li><strong>Insufficient Analysis</strong> : Developers may skip thorough system analysis in favor of a workable prototype, which might lead to subpar design decisions.</li>
<li><strong>Increased Cost</strong> : If the project is big and complicated, it might be expensive to make adjustments and prototype it again.</li>
<li><strong>Time-consuming</strong> : If the prototype requires several iterations, the iterative nature may cause the development process to drag on.</li>
<li><strong>User Expectations</strong> : Users may assume that the prototype is the finished product and anticipate a speedy delivery of the real system.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Draw a reduced decision table for the following scenario:<br />
An applicant has to fill up the form to participate in a music competition. The applicant’s age should be greater than 18 years and nationality has to be Nepalese for being selected for the competition. The applicant will be provided a registration number after paying Rs. 5000 as an entry fee. The applicant has to play an instrument for three minutes else will be disqualified. The experts will provide points on the basis of some criteria. The applicant having the highest point will be declared winner and will get a cash prize of Rs. 1,00,000 and all the qualified applicants will get a gift hamper.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>given,</p>
