<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Differentiate between black box and white box testing. Explain the testing process.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The differences between black box and white box testing are as follows:</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>Black box testing</strong></td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>White box testing</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">The testing methodology concentrated on the software&#8217;s functioning rather than its internal code structure.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It is software testing methodology that looks into the program&#8217;s internal organization, logic, and code.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">The only thing taken into consideration is input-output; no programming expertise is necessary.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It demands complete understanding of the structure, logic, and code.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It is most often carried out by end users or QA testers.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Usually carried out by testers or developers with coding experience.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Verify the software&#8217;s operation and behavior in accordance with the specifications.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Validate the code&#8217;s accuracy, effectiveness, and security.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It focuses on evaluating software&#8217;s functionality, including data management, user interface, and input validation.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">It examines internal code structure, including branching, loops, and code pathways.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>The process of testing are as follows:</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Inspections</span></strong>: This type of testing involves participants looking for predicted, language-specific mistakes in software code. Other automated inspection applications can check for grammar, syntax, and other issues.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Desk checking</span></strong>: It is the process by which a programmer goes over the code with a notepad and pencil after comprehending the program&#8217;s logic. The reviewer assumes the role of a computer, mentally verifying each step and its outcome for the complete set of computer commands.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Unit checking</span></strong>: It is an automated testing technique where each module is examined independently to look for potential code issues.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Integration testing</span></strong>: It is the process of combining many program modules for testing reasons.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">System testing</span></strong>: It is the process of assembling all of the programs that make up a system in order to test it. Black box or white box testing can be used to test the system.</p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Stub testing</span></strong>: It is a technique used to test modules, particularly when they are developed and tested top-down.</p>
</div>
<h2>SECTION B: Attempt any EIGHT question.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Briefly explain different phases of project management.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Project management</strong> is the systematic process of starting, organizing, carrying out, overseeing, managing, and ending a project. A project management process is guided by these five phases:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-43935" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/project-management.drawio.png?resize=184%2C244&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="184" height="244"></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Initiating</strong>:<br />
The project plan and viability are established during this stage. All significant stakeholders will be contacted by project managers in order to collect project requirements. The project proposal comprises the budget, timetable, resources, goals, and important stakeholders.</li>
<li><strong>Planning</strong>:<br />
The project managers will then draft a plan or map that includes all of the activities and deliverables for the project. Along with other stakeholders and resources, a comprehensive timetable is developed to ensure the project stays on course.</li>
<li><strong>Executing</strong>:<br />
During this stage, team members and project managers carry out the plans and construct the project. To keep the project on schedule, requirements and documentation are regularly reviewed and updated.</li>
<li><strong>Monitoring and Controlling</strong>:<br />
To guarantee project quality management and testing, project managers monitor and supervise ongoing activity, keeping it current and active. The project will remain on course with the support of frequent status meetings and assessments.</li>
<li><strong>Closing</strong>:<br />
The closing procedure is crucial because the project manager will carry out the project wrap-up and final documentation phase once the project has been finished and all deliverables have been met.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>How can CASE tool help in developing product? Explain with respect to different phases of SDLC.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>By offering automated help at different phases of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), <strong>Computer-Aided Software Engineering (CASE)</strong> technologies aid in the software development process. These technologies guarantee uniformity in software design, development, and maintenance while increasing efficiency and accuracy.</p>
<p>Here are some examples of how CASE tools may help at various stages of the SDLC:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Analysis Phase</strong> : CASE tools make it easier to capture, analyze, and manage requirements at this phase. They provide requirement documentation, model building, and change monitoring. Tools like Unified Modeling Language (UML) diagrams can be generated to represent use cases and requirements.</li>
<li><strong>System Design Phase : </strong>Data Flow Diagrams (DFD), Entity-Relationship Diagrams (ERD), and system architecture are among the architectural and comprehensive design diagrams that may be created during the design phase with the use of CASE tools.</li>
<li><strong>Coding Phase :</strong> CASE tools  increase coding productivity by supporting Integrated Development Environments (IDEs), automating code production, and enforcing coding standards. Tools like Eclipse, Visual Studio, and IBM Rational Application Developer.</li>
<li><strong>Testing Phase : </strong>Testing tools help with defect tracking, test case generation, and test execution automation. They lessen the need for manual testing while also enhancing software quality.</li>
<li><strong>Implementation and Deployment Phase</strong> : CASE tools facilitate the development of deployment scripts, automate configuration management, and guarantee a smooth deployment throughout this phase.</li>
<li><strong>Maintenance Phase</strong> : To guarantee the system runs smoothly during maintenance, CASE tools facilitate code analysis, problem fixes, and change management.</li>
</ol>
<p>To sum up, CASE tools are crucial to the SDLC since they guarantee that software effectively satisfies its intended requirements, streamline procedures, and increase accuracy.</p>
</div>
