<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>How do you think effective interfaces can be designed? Explain</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>For software to be user-friendly, satisfy users&#8217; demands, and improve their experience, effective interface design is crucial. Here are some essential guidelines and methods for creating user interfaces that work:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Simplicity</strong>: Maintain an uncomplicated, straightforward design. Eliminate extraneous components to prevent users from being overwhelmed and to help them concentrate on their work.</li>
<li><strong>Responsive design</strong>: Use of responsive design should be focused to make sure the user interface adapts and appears well across a range of screen sizes, including mobile devices and desktop displays.</li>
<li><strong>Touch-Friendly Features</strong>: To avoid unintentional clicks, make sure buttons and clickable regions on mobile interfaces are big enough to be readily touched and have enough space between them.</li>
<li><strong>Keyboard Navigation</strong>: It is crucial for those with motor limitations that the design be made keyboard accessible so that users may browse without a mouse.</li>
<li><strong>Feedback</strong>: Give users an explanation of their actions. For instance, loading indicators must to display progress and buttons ought to react graphically when pressed. Feedback enables users to determine if their actions were effective or whether more action is required.</li>
</ol>
<p>Having a thorough understanding of people and a dedication to usability, consistency, accessibility, and continuous development are key components of effective interface design. These guidelines help designers make interfaces that are not only useful but also enjoyable to use, guaranteeing a satisfying experience that satisfies user and corporate objectives.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>List the advantages of Normalization. Explain 2NF with an example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In order to increase data integrity and minimize redundancy, normalization is a method used in database architecture. In order to facilitate data storage and retrieval, it entails segmenting a database into smaller tables and establishing linkages between them.</p>
<p><strong>Advantages of Normalization</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Minimises Data Redundancy</strong>: Normalisation minimises duplicate data by arranging data into several relevant tables. The database is more effective and storage is saved as a result.</li>
<li><strong>Enhances Data Integrity</strong>: Normalization avoids discrepancies since data is kept in an organized manner. Data may be updated in a single location, guaranteeing correctness throughout the database.</li>
<li><strong>Improves Query Performance</strong>: Because normalized databases</li>
<li>require less processing of duplicated data, queries may be executed more quickly and effectively.</li>
<li><strong>Facilitates Data Maintenance</strong>: By allowing changes to be performed in a single location that will be reflected in all associated</li>
<li>tables, normalization makes it easier to add, remove, and update data.</li>
<li><strong>Prevents Update Anomalies</strong>: By appropriately arranging data, normalization minimizes the likelihood of several kinds of anomalies, including update, insert, and delete anomalies. This enhances the consistency of the data.</li>
</ol>
<p>To be in Second Normal Form (2NF), a table must have following:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>There are no recurring groups or arrays since it is in First Normal Form (1NF), which means all of the columns contain atomic values.</li>
<li>Every non-key attribute—a column that is not a part of the main key—depends on the complete primary key, not just a portion of it, in order to operate.</li>
</ul>
<p>This means that in 2NF, partial dependencies are removed — no non-key attribute depends only on a part of the primary key.</p>
<p>Suppose we have a table called <code>Orders</code> with the following structure:</p>
