<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain how disruptive technologies can be used in determining requirement.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Disruptive technologies are those that drastically change existing markets and value networks or develop new ones, ultimately displacing more established goods and technology. Particularly in domains such as software development, product design, or business strategy, these technologies may be extremely important in identifying needs.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Pattern Recognition</strong>: By analyzing enormous volumes of data, AI and ML are able to pinpoint user preferences, behavior patterns, and frequent problems. This can uncover hidden needs that conventional approaches might miss.</li>
<li><strong>Real-Time Data</strong>: By capturing real-time requirements and usage patterns, real-time analytics enable businesses to promptly adjust to changing user needs.</li>
<li><strong>Predictive Maintenance</strong>: Information gathered from Internet of Things sensors may forecast when parts may break or need to be upgraded, influencing specifications related to performance and durability.</li>
<li><strong>User testing and prototyping</strong>: Immersion prototyping is made possible by VR and AR, which let people experience and engage with a product concept in a virtual setting. This makes it easier to obtain more precise needs input prior to development.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Difference between process modeling and data modeling. How do you think data modeling play an important role?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The difference between process modeling and data modeling are:</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 144px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<th style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Aspect</th>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;"><strong>Process Modeling</strong></td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;"><strong>Data Modeling</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Focus</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">focuses on the information flow and system operation.</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">focuses on the types of data that are saved and their organization.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Purpose</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">outlines a process&#8217;s steps, stages, and sequences.</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">explains the entities, characteristics, and connections.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Representation</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Data flow diagrams (DFD), flowcharts etc are frequently used to illustrate this.</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Class diagrams or entity-relationship diagrams (ERD) are frequently used to illustrate this.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Usage</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">helpful for comprehending relationships, interconnections, and processes.</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">helpful for maintaining data integrity and creating the database structure.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 33.2707%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">Emphasis</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">focuses on operations and activities.</td>
<td style="width: 33.3333%; height: 24px; text-align: center;">focuses on connections  and data storage.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Data modeling is crucial for several reasons:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Data Integrity and Consistency</strong>: Data modeling ensures data consistency throughout the system by defining relationships and limitations. To guarantee that every order is constantly connected to an existing client, for instance, links between orders and customers are modeled.</li>
<li><strong>Enhanced Data Security</strong>: Data modeling helps to ensure that sensitive information is safeguarded by specifying access levels and connections.</li>
<li><strong>Adaptability and Scalability</strong>: Data models facilitate change in response to evolving needs. As a blueprint, the data model facilitates the addition of new entities or characteristics to a system without affecting its current architecture.</li>
<li><strong>Better System Performance</strong>: Thoughtful data models enable effective indexing and queries, which may greatly improve response times and system performance.</li>
<li><strong>Effective database design</strong> : It minimizes the possibility of duplication and ensures effective data retrieval by preventing data redundancy and optimizing storage.</li>
</ol>
<p>In conclusion, data modeling is a fundamental stage in system development that makes it possible to create an organized, dependable, and efficient database—all of which are necessary for efficient data management and organizational decision-making.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>An initial investment of Rs. 1,00,000 is required to start a company. The cash flow-in is Rs. 40,000 per year. Assuming interest rate as 10%, calculate the discounted payback period. (use Net Present Value)</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given Data:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Initial Investment = Rs. 1,00,000</li>
<li>Annual Cash Flow = Rs. 40,000</li>
<li>Discount Rate (Interest Rate) = 10%</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Calculating discounted Payback Period for each year using the formula: </strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$${Discounted Cash Flow} = \frac{\text{Cash Flow}}{(1 + Discount Rate)^n}</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">$$</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>where n represents the year.</p>
<p>Until the total is equal to or greater than the initial investment, add up the discounted cash flows.</p>
<p><strong>​Yearly Discounted Cash Flows:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$Year 1$$ = \frac{40,000}{(1 + 0.10)^1} = 36,364$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$Year 2 = \frac{40,000}{(1 + 0.10)^2} = 33,058$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$Year 3 = \frac{40,000}{(1 + 0.10)^3} = 30,050$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Accumulation of Discounted Cash Flows:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Year 1: 36,364</li>
<li>Year 2: 36,364 + 33,058 = 69,422</li>
<li>Year 3: 69,422 + 30,050 = 99,472</li>
</ul>
<p>The total discounted cash flow after three years is around Rs. 99,472, which is quite near to the Rs. 1,000,000 initial investment. As a result, the discounted repayment period is little over three years.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on :</p>
<ol>
<li>PERT</li>
<li>Deliverables</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<li><strong>PERT</strong> :<br />
The phases of system development, from preliminary analysis to final implementation, are planned using PERT, a project scheduling and management tool. In system projects, it aids in visualizing the order and relationships of tasks. PERT is especially helpful throughout the SDLC&#8217;s Planning and Analysis stages. It diagrams intricate procedures and aids in projecting deadlines at every stage, including requirement collection, system design, coding, testing, and deployment.<br />
In order to lower project risks and increase completion rates, PERT in SAD makes sure that every stage of system development is planned well, resources are distributed suitably, and possible bottlenecks are found early.</li>
<li><strong>Deliverables</strong> :<br />
The physical results of every stage of the system development process are known as deliverables. They are frequently used to indicate project milestones and contain objects made to fulfill certain goals in each stage of the SDLC. Deliverables offer an organized means of verifying the correctness and completeness of every stage. By making sure that every phase satisfies the needs of the stakeholders before proceeding to the next, they improve project accountability.<br />
Deliverables guarantee that stakeholders are in agreement on the design, needs, and advancement of the system. Clear deliverables facilitate better communication and project tracking, enabling stakeholders and the project team to know what has been done and what still need work.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</body></html>